Options for Curative Treatment of Localized Prostate Cancer.

Knipper S, Ott S, Schlemmer HP, Grimm MO, Graefen M, Wiegel T.

BACKGROUND: Prostate cancer is the most frequently occurring malignancy among 
men in Germany, with 60 000 new cases each year. Three of every four tumors are 
detected at an early, localized stage, when various curative treatment 
strategies are possible.
METHODS: A selective search of the literature in PubMed accompanied by 
consideration of guidelines from Germany and other countries.
RESULTS: Owing to the usually prolonged natural course of localized prostate 
cancer, local treatment is recommended for patients with a life expectancy of at 
least 10 years. The established treatments with curative intent are radical 
prostatectomy, percutaneous radiotherapy, and brachytherapy, with active 
surveillance as a further option for patients with low-risk disease. The 
eventual choice of treatment is determined by tumor stage, risk group, 
comorbidities, and patient preference. Conversations with the patient must cover 
not only the oncological outcome but also the potential adverse effects of the 
different treatment options. Depending on the procedure, urinary incontinence, 
erectile dysfunction, and inflammation of the bladder and/or rectum may be 
frequently occurring complications.
CONCLUSION: A number of curative and other treatments are available for patients 
with localized prostate cancer. The goal is to identify the appropriate option 
for each individual patient by means of detailed discussion.

