Survival Analysis of Geriatric Patients with Low Digestive Hemorrhage Attending 
an Emergency Department.

Fernandez-Suárez A(1), Yuguero Torres O(2).

Author information:
(1)Faculty of Medicine, University of Lleida, Lleida, Spain.
(2)Faculty of Medicine, University of Lleida, Lleida, Spain, 
oriol.yuguero@gmail.com.

BACKGROUND: The increase in life expectancy and low mortality have doubled the 
number of individuals older than 65 in the last 30 years.
METHODS: We conducted a retrospective study of 101 patients older than 80 years 
of age treated by low digestive hemorrhage (LDH) in an emergency department 
during 2018. Sociodemographic variables were evaluated, as well as comorbidity 
and survival at 18 months. Survival was assessed by a Kaplan-Meier test.
RESULTS: 52.5% of the subjects were women. The average comorbidity of the sample 
was 1.97. The survival rate per year was 60%. The finding on colonoscopy shows 
no association with mortality. However, those patients on 
anticoagulant/antiplatelet therapy have a higher survival rate.
CONCLUSION: Survival per year is high, so urgent colonoscopy for an LDH should 
be performed after evaluating the patient's stability and functional status in a 
scheduled and outpatient manner.

